{"questionId":"3234226","questionHtml":"<p>Two AC (alternating current) electrical sources with the same frequencies are combined. The<br>voltages from these sources can be expressed as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>°</mo><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>90</mn><mo>°</mo><mo>)</mo></math>.</p>\n<p>The combined total voltage can be expressed in the form <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>V</mi><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>θ</mi><mo>°</mo><mo>)</mo></math>.</p>\n<p>Determine the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi></math> and the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>METHOD 1 Analytical approach</strong></p>\n<p>attempt to express <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math> or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> in exponential form &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong> (M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>e.g. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>Im</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>6</mn><msup><mi>e</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mi>π</mi><mn>6</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mrow></msup><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>Im</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>6</mn><msup><mi>e</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mi>π</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mrow></msup><mo>)</mo></math></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Accept angles in radians or degrees.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>)</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>6</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mi>π</mi><mn>6</mn></mfrac></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mi>π</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></msup></math> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> This mark can be awarded even if seen as part of a correct larger expression.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></mrow></msup><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>6</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi>π</mi></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac></msup></mrow></mfenced></math> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>so <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3923</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>6</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>60</mn></math> (degrees)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Accept any value for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi></math> that rounds to a <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>sf answer of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>60</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>Do <strong>not</strong> accept a final answer for an angle in radians.</p>\n<p>Do <strong>not</strong> award <em><strong>A1</strong></em> for answer of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>60</mn><mo>°</mo></math> resulting from incorrect working.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 2 Graphical approach</strong></p>\n<p>let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi></math> and plot <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> curves on GDC&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; (M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/fa6bbe4fe59356d1e35d7eabddc4b370aa6d3698.png\"></p>\n<p>attempt to find maximum&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; (M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>attempt to find any <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-axis intercept (either <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>60</mn></math> or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>300</mn></math>)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn></math> (degrees) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>300</mn></math> (degrees)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 3 Geometric approach</strong></p>\n<p>considering the rhombus</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img src=\"__IMG__/e1b212d61a1b53204aa4d7a52b22979209da1f80.png\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>(M1)</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><msup><mn>6</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mn>6</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>6</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mn>120</mn><mo>°</mo></msqrt></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>108</mn></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3923</mn><mo>…</mo></math>)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn></math> (degrees)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; A2</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> An answer of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>300</mn></math>. is most likely to be seen in METHOD 2, but should be condoned in METHODS 1 and 3 if seen there.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[5 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"3234226","referenceCode":"23M.1.AHL.TZ1.12","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Two AC (alternating current) electrical sources with the same frequencies are combined. Thevoltages from these sources can be expressed as V1=6 sin (at+30°) and V2=6 sin (at+90°). ","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"12","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 5]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.13—Polar and Euler form"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}